I do have a few things I'd like to say. First, I did have to email the study co panel to find out when the study notifications would begin and  end for each day. Not the notifications themselves, because the specific times are randomized. but the earliest each day of the study would begin and the latest it would end. Also, I do think that there should be a few exceptions/exemptions in place for those who accidentally miss a notification activity and thus don't get paid for that individual activity. I think these exemptions should allow participants to still get paid if they miss a notification activity or two as long as they qualify for the exemption. I just have to hope I get an email response and that I don't lose out on precious pay due to an unforseen situation.

Not sure if it was my phone or the app, but for quite a few days (like 4 or 5?) I would not get the push notification for the surveys until after the window was closed, and both the initial 'survey open' push notification as well as the 'survey is still open' reminder push notification would push at the same time. This would happen even while I was actively using my phone, so I know it wasn't because I just didn't look at my phone or because my phone was locked. Secondly, your survey questions specifically refer to 'the thought' which in my opinion made it difficult to answer accurately because if I'm not completely focused on something, I usually have numerous thoughts in my head simultaneously or in rapid succession (as well as music playing constantly, but that's not really a thought so I guess it's irrelevant?). Also, it was difficult to know what to denote as 'the task' and 'the thought' if my attention was split fairly evenly amongst a few different things.

I enjoyed being part of this study! I would suggest to have the app ask if you are able to use your phone at the time the alert comes. If the person is able to use their phone then they can proceed to the questions, if they are not able to use their phone the survey should pause for 30 minutes or more to allow them time to go somewhere they can use their phone and respond. I missed out on a few surveys this week because I started a new job and was not able to use my phone during work hours unless on a break. Overall, this study was great to take part in and I hope you all have more research studies I can participate in in the future.
